      <bioghist id="aspace_eb8d9a87add02c3d490814cf8e545e3b">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>William Jay Foltz was Professor Emeritus of African Studies and Political Science at Yale University from 1963 until 2013. He was born in Mount Vernon, New York, in 1936 and received his A.B. at Princeton in 1957 and his Ph.D. from Yale in 1963. He was the first director of the Yale Center for International and Area Studies (now the Macmillan Center) from 1983 to 1989 where he greatly expanded faculty and university programs in international relations. He served as Chair of the Council on African Studies, Chair of the Political Science Department and was Associate Director of Yale's Southern African Research Program for 15 years. He was a consultant to the Rand Corporation and the U.S. Department of State. In addition, he was a Senior Fellow at the Council on Foreign Relations and served on the National Intelligence Council as the National Intelligence Officer for Africa from 1995 to 1997. Professor Foltz died in New Haven, Connecticut in October 2013.</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <prefercite id="aspace_7cd2a47e01478f1006ea82c9cdf4fc90">
